        "prompt_formatting": {
          "style": "all lowercase. written in a motivational yet conversational tone using first person \"i\" perspective when sharing personal experiences about wellness, managing stress, improving focus, and boosting energy naturally. write at a 7th grade reading level in a style that sounds like a supportive friend\n\nyou can also ask rhetorical questions. position yourself as someone who understands the struggle of prioritizing yourself and has found success. use short, punchy sentences. the writing should feel authentic, conversational, like you're talking with a good friend you love and trust. do not add any discourse markers in the text like \"honestly,\" \"trust me,\" \"frankly,\" \"to tell you the truth,\" or \"believe me\". remove these so called truth parentheticals or sincerity markers. the content should feel personal and relatable, creating a progression from recognizing self-deception to embracing personal truth about natural wellness practices and sustainable energy.",
          "narrative": "rules of emotional sobriety for people who feel everything too deeply\nhow i become the calmest person in every room\nthings i had to unlearn about love that i mistook for closeness\nthe science of detachment (why letting go is how you receive)\nthe quiet power of being unbothered (mastering the art of emotional sovereignty)\nthe art of being unbothered (how to stop letting people rent space in your head)\nhow i stopped needing external validation to feel like i was enough\nthings i learned about loneliness that no one says out loud\nrules of emotional maturity for people who feel everything but show nothing\nrules of emotional clarity for people who live inside their own head\nthings i had to unlearn about self-worth that i mistook for strength\nthe art of choosing yourself\nhow i became the person who no longer abandons herself to keep the peace\nthings i wish i knew about boundaries before i burned out trying to save everyone\nhow i stopped apologizing for taking up space in my own life\nrules of emotional independence for people who used to need everyone's approval\nthe quiet shift that happens when you stop performing for people who don't see you\nthings i had to unlearn about anger that i mistook for weakness\nhow i learned to sit with silence instead of filling it with noise\nrules of self-trust for people who second-guess everything they feel\nthe art of staying soft without letting people walk all over you\nthings i stopped doing when i realized peace mattered more than being liked\nhow i became someone who doesn't need closure to move on",
          "num_of_slides": 6
        },
